caption: I stumbled upon this place while walking down Wentworth in China Town searching for dinner. Ordered take out shrimp egg foo yung for the wife and orange chicken for myself. I never thought that finding Chinese food in China Town could be such an ordeal. Got home to find that the container for the efy (egg foo yung) had shifted and all the sauce wasted into the plastic bag it was packed inside. Imagine SEFY patties without the sauce. The orange chicken wasn't remarkable, just okay. All I wanted was some authentic Chinese food from China Town, and made a special trip for it, only to be so disappointed. I could have stayed in the hood and just taken my chances with the usual. Oh, well.

This Cantonese restaurant had been around since at least the 80s and is one of my favorites. I drop by this place every time I visit Chinatown. It has a large menu but I think its forte is the Cantonese noodles, either soupy or dry. It has kept the price very low and you get very good value here. One of their specialties is roast meats,  roast duck, roast pork, char siu, etc. The roast duck is specifically good. You can buy by the pounds for take out.

I'm going to have to work up to the $170 Japanese Kobe cut, though. I may not be man enough yet.

Native of Chicago, have been going to Seven Treasure for nearly 4 decades. Restaurant is a Chicago classic among the natives. This place is on the dive side, but is famous for its Hong Kong style wheat flour noodle, and their won-ton dumpling soup with noodles, with the classic red vinegar! The red vinegar is incredible in this place.  The poor reviews are from tourist expecting PF Chang / Panda Express Americanized Chinese food, and are offended by authentic Cantonese Hong Kong style cooking. Chicago classic. You will find a lot of natives eating here, which is a sign of a true ethnic restaurant. Plus due to late hours, is a hang out for people out late especially on the weekends.

7 Treasures has been one of my most favorite restaurants in Chinatown since my early college days!

Simple, easy going place with menu catering to the local Cantonese population.  This is a joint to fill your palate with your own cravings from the Olde World, but this is not a place to see people and to be seen.  Being in operation for more than 30 years, this is one of the original Chinatown anchors on Wenworth Ave.  Famous for their Won Ton Noodle Soup, always a good treat in cold weather.  Their menu a la carte is decent, but as a foodie, I do not recommend the Chinese BBQ plate; the neck of the roasted duck has been hung a bit too long....  Bathroom is clean but tiny, typical of Chinatown space-saving campaign.
